//For user input until they’re done: Use sentinel-controlled repetition with a while loop.
//Why: You don’t know how many inputs the user will give. So you pick a special "stop" value called a sentinel. You keep looping and asking for input while the user hasn’t entered that sentinel. The loop might run zero times if they quit immediately.
//For factorial of 5: Use counter-controlled repetition with a while or for loop.
//Why: You know exactly how many times to multiply: 5 times. So you set up a counter that goes from 1 to 5. Each time through the loop you multiply by the counter, then increase the counter. When the counter goes past 5, you stop. The number of repetitions is known before the loop starts.
